[2] Nicaragua
Date: Mon 19 Oct 2009
Source: Prensa Latina [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.prensa-latina.cu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=127286&Itemid=5>


Managua, the capital of the country, is the [area] hardest hit by the
dengue epidemic that is affecting the country, as indicated today [19
Oct 2009] by data from the Ministry of Health (MINSA).

The office of the director of Health Surveillance indicated that as
of this Monday [19 Oct 2009], 1869 confirmed cases and 8 deaths have
been registered in the country. Of this total, 1818 are classical
dengue and 51 are DHF, with children 5-14 years of age the most
affected. The report stresses that the municipality of Managua is the
area with most registered classical dengue and DHF [cases], followed
by Masaya, Carazo, Leon, Chinandega, Boaco, Chontales, Matagalpa, the
South Atlantic Autonomous Region, and Rio San Juan.

Reports from the Pan American Health Organization point out that in
the [Central American] region there are 730 000 [reported] cases of
dengue, including 16 545 DHF cases with 289 deaths.

