[3] Dominican Republic
Date: Wed 21 Oct 2009
Source: Listin Diario.com [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.listindiario.com.do/app/article.aspx?id=118816>


The country is facing a dengue epidemic which this year [2009] has
affected 3788 people and caused the deaths of 27 patients, mainly
children, announced the undersecretary of Community Health, Nelson
Rodriguez Monegro, yesterday [20 Oct 2009]. He explained that the
number of cases exceeded by more than 1000 the [dengue cases]
registered last year [2008], and that DHF cases, 238 as of yesterday
(20 Oct 2009], have duplicated those of 2008.

Rodriguez Monegro stated that in 70 percent of the Dominican homes,
there are breeding sites of the mosquito that is the vector of the
disease [virus].

He attributed the mortality [rate] as due to the failure of hospital
and clinic physicians to provide [adequate] attention to patients,
who require surveillance 24 hours [a day], and weakness in the
management of health centers.

He called on families, communities, neighborhood associations, local
governments, and the other organized sectors of the country to come
together to eliminate mosquito breeding sites. He complained that
some politicians are offering spraying in neighborhoods and
communities without taking into account the technical criteria that
must prevail at the time of spraying, which, he pointed out, is not
the ideal solution against dengue.

Dengue is a febrile illness [caused by a virus] spread by the bite of
a mosquito that breeds in clean water. It is recommended to clean the
surroundings of the homes and adequately cover [containers for] water
stored for domestic consumption. The undersecretary said that
wherever cases have been identified there has been intervention in
the community to eliminate all vector mosquito breeding sites. He
cited the case of San Cristobal, which had house-to-house action
because the neighborhood had 6 children from the Moscu neighborhood
admitted in the Robert Reid Cabral Children's Hospital. In the home
of one these children, 8 mosquito breeding sites were found and in
another one, 20 automobile tires were found, which are real [vector
mosquito] breeding sites. He explained that a 55 gallon [208 liter]
water storage tank is able to produce 80-120 mosquitoes daily, which
is why they must be well covered. "If families dedicate themselves to
cleaning up their homes, roofs, patios, change water in flower vases
on alternate days, and the community is vigilant and removes trash,
they will not have dengue," he said.

He reminded everyone that dengue is a disease that exceeds the
boundaries of health, because of the influence of the environment,
the work of municipalities, water service, and supervision of
families.

The president of the Dominican Association of Physicians, Waldo Ariel
Suero, indicated that in the country there is considerable
underreporting of dengue cases and that the real numbers are 4-5
times higher than those registered by the epidemiological
surveillance system. He said that this underreporting is large
because private clinics and hospitals do not notify [authorities of]
the surveillance system of those ambulatory cases that they see,
which are 4-5 times more than those [cases] reported to Public
Health. He explained that the cases that are captured by the
surveillance system are those of seriously ill patients that have to
be admitted [to hospitals or clinics]. In his opinion, the increase
in dengue cases are due to the lack of planning by the Secretariat of
Public Health, which cyclically abandons preventive work.

[Byline: Doris Pantaleon]

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Dominican health authorities have now acknowledged that the
country is facing a dengue epidemic. Controlling it will be a
challenge. It is easy to make the case for mounting household and
community programs to reduce or eliminate _Aedes aegypti_ breeding
sites in and around houses and other buildings. However,
accomplishing and sustaining that task has proved enormously
difficult. Only 2 countries, Singapore and Cuba, were successful, and
even they were unable to maintain the effort and suffered dengue
outbreaks after several years without cases. Clearly, an
environmentally friendly, low cost, less labor intensive approach to
vector control is needed until such time that a safe, effective,
inexpensive vaccine becomes available.

[A map of the Dominican Republic can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/dominican_republic_pol_04.jpg>.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the Dominican Republic can
be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00NY>. - Mod.TY]

