[5] Brazil (Parana)
Date: Wed 21 Oct 2009
Source: Bem Parana [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.bemparana.com.br/index.php?n=124642&t=maringa-ja-teve-56-casos-de-dengue-em-2009>


The Municipal Committee to Combat Dengue on Wednesday (21 [Oct 2009])
announced a work strategy for 14 Nov [2009], "D-day against dengue"
as defined by the state Secretariat of Health. "One day is just a
little and every sector involved in the committee should begin its
preparation for the week to discard trash that we will promote in the
1st half of November [2009], "said secretary of health, Antonio
Carlos Nardi.

With 56 confirmed [dengue] cases this year [2009], the same number as
in 2008, the proposal is to mobilize all sectors of the Committee
members' [areas] for a functional result. The intent, says Nardi, is
to mobilize between 700 and 1000 people, inform the communities to be
worked with, and remove as much trash that accumulates water from
homes and land as possible.

The coordinator of Environmental Surveillance of the Secretariat of
Health, Mariangela Felix Vecchi, added that the trash collection will
be concentrated in areas having the greatest mosquito index according
to the latest survey. The residents should put on the sidewalks all
the material that can accumulate water and must be discarded.

The secretary Antonio Carlos Nardi points out that the rains of
recent weeks and hot weather are factors that can lead to rapid
proliferation of the mosquito, and an increasing number of cases.
"From now until May [2010] all of Brazil is at risk of a dengue
epidemic, with serious consequences, and Maringa also runs this
risk," he said. "So everyone should adopt the habit of eliminating
standing water."

--
