[7] Brazil (Minas Gerais)
Date: Thu 22 Oct 2009
Source: Correo de Uberlandia [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.correiodeuberlandia.com.br/texto/2009/10/22/41044/casos_de_dengue_aumentam_7,75.html>


The increase in the frequency of rains during the months of August
and September this year [2009] was the factor noted for the increase
in the household infestation indices of the mosquito _Aedes aegypti_
and the confirmed dengue cases in Uberlandia. From January to
September 2008, 271 cases of classical dengue were confirmed. Up to
September this year [2009], 292 people have had this disease, which
represents 8 percent more cases in relation to the same period last
year [2008].

Already the rapid [house] infestation indexes for _Aedes aegypti_
have reached 1.2 percent in October of this year [2009], surpassing
the 0.8 percent from October 2008. According to the coordinator of
the dengue control program in Uberlandia, Jose Humberto Arruda, the
difference in the numbers was because it rained more in recent months
than it did in the same seasonal period in 2008. "This indicates
that, for every 100 buildings in the city, 1.2 have the vector
mosquito that transmits the disease [virus]. This does not indicate a
disequilibrium or epidemic, but the rainy months require more
precautions," said Arruda.

Today [22 Oct 2009], 352 agents of zoonosis control are working to
visit 243 000 buildings in Uberlandia. The average is one visit to
each property within 2 months. "The frequency of inspection cannot be
greater than the replacement of foci of the mosquito [breeding
sites]. Therefore, it is vital to have a partnership with every
citizen for the constant elimination of standing water," said the
coordinator for Control of Dengue. Both the poor and the wealthy
neighborhoods of Uberlandia have foci of the mosquito that transmits
dengue [virus].

[This report provides January-September data for dengue cases in
Uberlandia for 2007, 2008, and 2009, household infestation rates of
_Ae. aegypti_ for the most infested neighborhoods and overall
infestation rates for Uberlandia, as well as control and surveillance
campaign plans. - Mod.TY]

[Byline: Angelica Peixoto]

